# Merge Conflicts: No Behavioral Changes

When fixing git merge conflicts, the hardest guardrail is: **no behavioral change beyond conflict resolution**.

- Treat conflict resolution as preservation work, not a feature, bug fix, refactor, cleanup, or formatting pass.
- Only choose between, combine, or minimally reconcile the already-conflicting sides.
- Do not introduce new logic, dependency changes, test expectation changes, formatting churn, or opportunistic fixes while resolving conflicts.
- If the sides are incompatible and resolving them requires a product, architecture, or behavioral decision, stop and ask the user instead of inventing a third behavior.
- After resolving, report which conflicts were resolved and call out any behavioral decisions that remain unresolved.
